April 12 at 9:24pm ·

For decades, the death of a slave in the Battle of Appomattox Court House at the end of the Civil War was considered a tragedy of historical circumstance.

But the story was incomplete, an Appomattox pastor realized.

Discovery Gives New Ending To A Death At The Civil War's Close
Hannah Reynolds, a slave, was the only civilian killed in the Battle of Appomattox Court House during the Civil War. A new discovery suggests, contrary to earlier...
www.npr.org|By All Things Considered

  • Logan Anderson A correction to the story. In the next-to-last graf, you say it was first reported by The Associated Press. Not the case. It was first reported by The News & Advance, the daily newspaper in Lynchburg in early March. The AP then picked the story from the N&A and did its own story a month later.

    http://www.newsadvance.com/.../article_ddcb8698-c536-11e4...
    'Wounded as a slave, died as a free woman:' Appomattox anniversary program to honor Hannah Reynolds
    In 1865, Hannah Reynolds was a house slave living near Appomattox with Dr. Samuel H. Coleman and his wife Amanda Abbitt Coleman.
    newsadvance.com
